        "option_4": "<p style=\"orphans:2;widows:2\"> <span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span><span style=\"font-style:normal\"><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"font-weight:normal\">Neither 1 nor 2 is correct</span></span></span></span></span></p>",
        "option_5": "",
        "answer": "2",
        "solution": "<p style=\"orphans:2;widows:2\"> <span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span><span style=\"font-style:normal\"><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"font-weight:normal\">The Trinity of Carnatic Music refers to</span></span></span></span><span><span style=\"font-style:normal\"><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><b>Tyagaraja, Muthuswami Dikshitar, and Shyama Shastri</b></span></span></span><span><span style=\"font-style:normal\"><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"font-weight:normal\">, who are regarded as the greatest composers of Carnatic music. They did</span></span></span></span><span><span style=\"font-style:normal\"><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><b>not belong to the 17th century</b></span></span></span><span><span style=\"font-style:normal\"><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"font-weight:normal\">but to the</span></span></span></span><span><span style=\"font-style:normal\"><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><b>18th–19th centuries</b></span></span></span><span><span style=\"font-style:normal\"><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"font-weight:normal\">(Tyagaraja: 1767–1847, Dikshitar: 1775–1835, Shyama Shastri: 1762–1827). <b>Hence,</b> Statement 1 is incorrect. However, it is true that the Trinity</span></span></span></span><span><span style=\"font-style:normal\"><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><b>developed and elevated the kriti form</b></span></span></span><span><span style=\"font-style:normal\"><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"font-weight:normal\">of Carnatic music, giving it its highest artistic and devotional expression. Thus, Statement 2 is correct.</span></span></span></span></span></p>"
