        "answer": "4",
        "solution": "<p style=\"orphans:2;widows:2\"> <span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span><span style=\"font-style:normal\"><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"font-weight:normal\">In Carnatic music,</span></span></span></span><span><i><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"font-weight:normal\">Varnam</span></span></i></span><span><span style=\"font-style:normal\"><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"font-weight:normal\">is not performed at the end but usually at the beginning of a concert. It serves as a warm-up piece, introducing the raga, testing the musician’s voice, and setting the tone for the performance. Therefore,</span></span></span></span><span><span style=\"font-style:normal\"><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><b>Statement 1 is incorrect</b></span></span></span><span><span style=\"font-style:normal\"><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"font-weight:normal\">. On the other hand,</span></span></span></span><span><i><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"font-weight:normal\">Alapana</span></span></i></span><span><span style=\"font-style:normal\"><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"font-weight:normal\">is indeed an improvisational elaboration of a raga without any fixed rhythm (</span></span></span></span><span><i><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"font-weight:normal\">tala</span></span></i></span><span><span style=\"font-style:normal\"><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"font-weight:normal\">). The artist explores the raga slowly, moving from lower notes to higher, showcasing creativity and mastery. Thus,</span></span></span></span><span><span style=\"font-style:normal\"><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><b>Statement 2 is correct</b></span></span></span><span><span style=\"font-style:normal\"><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"font-weight:normal\">, making option 4 the right answer.</span></span></span></span></span></p>"
