        "answer": "2",
        "solution": "<p style=\"orphans:2;widows:2\"> <span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span><span style=\"font-style:normal\"><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"font-weight:normal\">Both statements are correct.</span></span></span></span><span><span style=\"font-style:normal\"><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><b>Kriti</b></span></span></span><span><span style=\"font-style:normal\"><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"font-weight:normal\">is indeed a highly structured and central musical composition in the Carnatic music tradition. It usually consists of three main parts: Pallavi, Anupallavi, and Charanam . Kritis are devotional in nature and are the backbone of Carnatic performances. On the other hand,</span></span></span></span><span><span style=\"font-style:normal\"><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><b>Tillana</b></span></span></span><span><span style=\"font-style:normal\"><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"font-weight:normal\">is a lively and rhythmic composition that is often used to conclude Carnatic recitals. It places emphasis on rhythmic syllables (jatis) and is known for its brisk tempo and lively character. <b>Hence,</b> both statements accurately describe important aspects of Carnatic music.</span></span></span></span></span></p>"
