        "solution": "<p style=\"orphans:2;widows:2\"> <span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span><span style=\"font-style:normal\"><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"font-weight:normal\">The correct answer is</span></span></span></span><span><span style=\"font-style:normal\"><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><b>Mridangam</b></span></span></span><span><span style=\"font-style:normal\"><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"font-weight:normal\">. In Carnatic classical music, which is the classical music tradition of South India, the Mridangam is the primary percussion instrument. It is a double-headed drum made of wood with leather on both sides. One side produces a bass sound and the other produces a treble sound, making it versatile for accompanying vocal as well as instrumental performances. While instruments like the Santoor and Shehnai are associated with Hindustani classical music of North India, and Dhol is used in folk traditions, Mridangam remains central to Carnatic performances.</span></span></span></span></span></p>"
